# EmailJS Configuration
# Get these values from your EmailJS dashboard at https://www.emailjs.com/
# 1. Create an account and service
# 2. Create an email template
# 3. Get your public key from Account > API Keys

NEXT_PUBLIC_EMAILJS_SERVICE_ID=your_service_id_here
NEXT_PUBLIC_EMAILJS_TEMPLATE_ID=your_template_id_here
NEXT_PUBLIC_EMAILJS_PUBLIC_KEY=your_public_key_here

# Note: These are NEXT_PUBLIC_ variables because EmailJS runs in the browser.
# They will be visible in the client-side bundle, which is acceptable for EmailJS.
# Do not put sensitive server-side secrets here.

# Instructions for EmailJS Setup:
# 1. Go to https://www.emailjs.com/ and create a free account
# 2. Create a new Email Service (Gmail, Outlook, etc.)
# 3. Create an Email Template with these variables:
#    - {{from_name}} - Customer name
#    - {{from_email}} - Customer email
#    - {{from_phone}} - Customer phone
#    - {{service_interest}} - Service they're interested in
#    - {{message}} - Their message
#    - {{to_name}} - Your name (Josh Cagle)
#    - {{submission_date}} - When form was submitted
# 4. Copy your Service ID, Template ID, and Public Key to this file
# 5. Rename this file to .env.local (remove .example)
# 6. The contact form will automatically use these credentials